{"id": 225012698, "title": "Delhi Hits Record 126 F Degrees As Extreme Heat Wave Envelops North India", "text": "Share to Facebook Share to Twitter Share to Linkedin Topline The temperature in New Delhi soared to a record high of 126.1 degrees Fahrenheit (52.3 degrees Celsius) on Wednesday as India\u2019s capital and several other parts of the country reeled from a dangerous heat wave that has claimed dozens of lives. Temperatures hit a record high in New Delhi as northern India reels from a severe heatwave. AFP via Getty Images Key Facts A weather station in the northwest Delhi neighborhood of Mungeshpur registered the record-high temperature at 2.30 p.m. local time on Wednesday. The temperature comes amid an ongoing heat wave across parts of northwest and central India, with the temperature in the capital regularly nearing the 50-degree Celsius mark over the past few days. The India Meteorological Department said the extreme heat conditions will gradually reduce starting Thursday. An IMD official told the Press Trust of India that certain areas in the national capital are \u201cparticularly susceptible\u201d to the arrival of hot winds from the neighboring state of Rajasthan, leading to severe temperatures. Earlier on Wednesday, the weather agency issued a \u2018Red Alert\u2019\u2014its highest warning level\u2014across several North Indian states urging people to take precautions and remain indoors. News Peg At least 60 heat-related deaths were reported across the country between March 1 and last week, Mint reported, citing data from the National Centre for Disease Control. The toll includes 32 deaths due to heatstroke and 28 from suspected heatstroke. Local media reported at least three additional deaths this week in the northwestern state of Rajasthan\u2014which has been the worst hit. Since the start of March, at least 16,344 suspected cases of heatstroke have been reported across the country, the Mint report added. Big Number 237 gigawatts. That is the total power demand across India recorded on Thursday\u2014a seasonal high. India\u2019s ministry of power expects demand to remain just as high for the rest of May before rising above 240 GW in June. In its most recent report, the International Energy Agency said global carbon emissions hit a record high in 2023\u2014heavily driven by rising power demand in India and China. What To Watch For The final phase of India\u2019s national elections is set to take place on June 1\u2014if the extreme heat wave continues, it will likely impact turnout. Further Reading Delhi Hits 52.3 Degrees, Highest-Ever Recorded Temperature In India (NDTV) India records over 16,000 heatstroke cases, 60 deaths since 1 March (Mint) Follow me on Twitter. Send me a secure tip. Siladitya Ray Following Editorial Standards Print Reprints & Permissions", "summary": "At least 60 heat-related deaths have been reported across India since the beginning of March.", "url": "https://www.forbes.com/sites/siladityaray/2024/05/29/delhi-hits-record-126-f-degrees-as-extreme-heat-wave-envelops-north-india/", "image": "https://imageio.forbes.com/specials-images/imageserve/6657202d7b5c53fd9eae3a4a/0x0.jpg?format=jpg&crop=2131,1199,x0,y110,safe&height=900&width=1600&fit=bounds", "video": null, "publish_date": "2024-05-29 12:33:57", "author": "Forbes Staff,Siladitya Ray", "authors": ["Forbes Staff", "Siladitya Ray"], "language": "en", "source_country": "US", "sentiment": -0.169}